it.jrc.lt.core.component.matcher

Class BasicMatcher

  • java.lang.Object
    • it.jrc.lt.core.component.Component
      • it.jrc.lt.core.component.matcher.AbstractMatcher
        • it.jrc.lt.core.component.matcher.BasicMatcher
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Storable

    public final class BasicMatcher
extends AbstractMatcher
    basic implementation of matcher. this implementation expects pattern files with the following format: pattern | ATTR-NAME # attr-value # ATTR-NAME # attr-value ... - on normal pattern lines: - default field separator is | - default separator between attr-name and attr-value is # - no surface value is expected (because when a pattern matches, the matching text is returned) - prefix-ignoring patterns for MatchWords (i.e. Al- ו (Hebrew Waw) ...) can also added in the pattern file - just add them wherever in the pattern file as an own line (i.e. @Al-'] @ו] ...) without '| ATTR-NAME # attr-value' - prefix-ignoring is not needed anymore for apostrophe (nowadays apostrophe is a + character) - prefix-ignoring has been designed especially for semitic languages - to match, the word following a prefix must be lowercase - first line in pattern file must be empty line (otherwise a pattern is built where first character is the utf8 control character... and it will never match) given these constraints, _mattributes will be a map (populated at runtime) of combinations; and MatchWords (_mw) facet will just be a byte corresponding to the index in _mattributes note about erik's pattern: -house% -- house, housewife -house_ -- housed, houses
    Author:
    dellale
